  "text": "The Java bytecode to JIT compiled code chain in OpenJDK involves the following stages:\n\n1. **CompileBroker Request** (src/hotspot/share/compiler/compileBroker.hpp/.cpp): CompileBroker::compile_method is the top-level entry point for all compilation requests. It manages compilation queues and dispatches compilation tasks to compiler threads.\n\n2. **C2 Compiler Entry Point** (src/hotspot/share/opto/c2compiler.hpp/.cpp): C2Compiler::compile_method (defined in c2compiler.cpp at line 117) is invoked by CompileBroker. This is the C2 optimizer (tier-2 JIT compiler) entry point. It creates an Options object and instantiates the Compile object, handling compilation retries with different optimization levels.\n\n3. **Compilation Orchestration** (src/hotspot/share/opto/compile.hpp/.cpp): The Compile class (defined at compile.hpp line 224) serves as the top-level compilation coordinator. It orchestrates all compilation phases including bytecode parsing, intermediate representation construction, optimizations, register allocation, and code generation.\n\n4. **Bytecode-to-Ideal-Graph Conversion** (src/hotspot/share/opto/parse.hpp and parse1.cpp/parse2.cpp/parse3.cpp): The Parse class (defined at parse.hpp line 150, inherits from GraphKit) is responsible for parsing Java bytecode and converting it into an Ideal graph (sea-of-nodes intermediate representation). The Parse class walks through bytecode instructions and creates corresponding Node objects using GraphKit utilities. Parse files are split: parse1.cpp contains the main parsing logic, parse2.cpp and parse3.cpp contain bytecode-specific parsing methods, and parseHelper.cpp provides helper functions.\n\n5. **Graph Building Support** (src/hotspot/share/opto/graphKit.hpp/.cpp): GraphKit (defined at graphKit.hpp line 58) is a toolkit for building the common sorts of subgraphs. It manages the JVM state during parsing, handles value stack operations, and creates intermediate graph nodes. It does not know about bytecode parsing directly but provides the infrastructure for Parse to create nodes.\n\n6. **Node Representation** (src/hotspot/share/opto/node.hpp/.cpp): Node class (node.hpp) is the fundamental building block of the Ideal graph. Each Java bytecode operation is represented as a sea-of-nodes graph where nodes represent operations and edges represent data and control dependencies.\n\n7. **Code Generation and Installation** (src/hotspot/share/opto/output.hpp/.cpp): PhaseOutput class handles the final stages of compilation. The install() method (line 3399) and install_code() method (line 3413) in output.cpp register the compiled method. install_code() calls C->env()->register_method which triggers nmethod creation and code cache installation.\n\n8. **Native Method Creation** (src/hotspot/share/code/nmethod.hpp/.cpp): nmethod::new_nmethod() (defined at nmethod.cpp line 1122) is the factory method that creates a compiled method object. It allocates memory for the nmethod object, copies debug information, dependencies, and compiled code into appropriate sections, and installs the nmethod into the code cache under the CodeCache_lock.\n\n9. **Code Cache Management** (src/hotspot/share/code/codeCache.hpp/.cpp): CodeCache is the memory management system that stores all compiled code. When nmethod::new_nmethod() creates an nmethod, the code is stored in the code cache, and the nmethod becomes executable at the entry point address."
